&gt;Completely, utterly, and totally different concepts.  The US DoD
&gt;Internet Domain Name System has nothing to do with the ISO structure
&gt;for the identification of organizations.  The DoD does not have to
&gt;play footsie to the lords of ISO to do things within the Internet
&gt;Protocol suite!  The Internet Engineering Task Force is not an ISO
&gt;subcommitee, we are free men!  The Network Information Center is the
&gt;*root* of the domain name system tree, and can establish whatever
&gt;structure it (really DCA) desires.

The problem is that although, x.500, DNS, and DNANS are all absolute,
tree-structured, naming systems, there is no effort to standardize the
name spaces.  I don't see why we need totally separate names, name
spaces, etc.

All of this "live free or die" talk ignores two facts: there is some of
OSI that we might profitably steal, and "politically correct" is
occasionally the most significant bit in evaluating what gets
funded/supported.

paul

